Issue is in the 3d branch. I am currently porting a game from WP7 XNA to WIndows 8 Metro using MonoGame With SharpDX.

Exception is thrown by the following line:
graphicsDevice._d3dContext.CopySubresourceRegion(_texture, level, null, stagingTex, 0, 0, 0, 0);

Seems like the implementation of CopySubresourceRegion is missing in the SharpDX 2.2.0.7 build implementation (SharpDX.Direct3D11.dll) and not in the MonoGame framework itself. Strange, because whoever did the job first time would have the SharpDX implementation correct.

I am using the MonoGame GetData Method to pick a texture area from a sprite:
Texture2DSpriteSheet.GetData(0, rec1, col1, 0, scoreNumber.Width \* scoreNumber.Height);

The MonoGame Effect processor doesn't seem to accept render states in passes:

```
technique Technique1
{
    pass Pass1
    {
        CullMode = None;
        AlphaBlendEnable = TRUE;
        DestBlend = INVSRCALPHA;
        SrcBlend = SRCALPHA;

        VertexShader = compile vs_2_0 VertexShaderFunction();
        PixelShader = compile ps_2_0 PixelShaderFunction();
    }
}
```

More specifically, the CullMode, AlphaBlendEnable, DestBlend and SrcBlend lines are the problem. When removed, the FX is compiled and works, but then the render states aren't set.

Is this something that is planned to be supported / should work?

When compiling a pretty basic FX file with a Texture parameter defined as:

```
uniform extern texture Texture;
```

and a texture sampler defined as:

```
sampler textureSampler = sampler_state
{
    Texture = <Texture>;
    mipfilter = POINT; 
    minfilter = POINT; 
    magfilter = POINT; 
};
```

XNA exposes an effect parameter named "Texture" whereas MonoGame exposes the same parameter as "textureSampler". This means I have to change my code from

```
Effect.Parameters["Texture"] = myTexture;
```

to

```
Effect.Parameters["textureSampler"] = myTexture;
```

I have a concept of controls in my application. One of them is a text field which has a width and height property.
When rendering text I set GraphicsDevice.ScissorRectangle so that the text is not rendered outside the bounds of the fields.

``` csharp
public override void Draw(SpriteBatch batch)
{
    batch.GraphicsDevice.ScissorRectangle = new Rectangle((int)Position.X, (int)Position.Y, Width, Height);
    batch.DrawString(Font, "SOME SAMPLE TEXT THAT IS LONGER THAN THE WIDTH OF THE FIELD", new Vector2(Position.X + textOffSetX, Position.Y + textOffSetY), Color.White, Rotation, Origin, Scale, Effects, 0);

When using XNA on Windows or MonoGame on Android the ScissorRectangle is respected,
on Linux with MonoGame (from the git repositoy, commit e1ccc226fdd8aa1b95d8918b78f5d94cf9147d99) the
text is rendered outside the bounds of the ScissorRectangle.

```
